A clerical error in the present volume regarding the year in which Mary of Gueldres died has been aheady adverted to. Wide as was the lati- tude of orthography allowed in proper names, spelh'ngs are found from time to time which can only be accounted for by the limited local knowledge of the writer of the roll. A wrong Α Christian name occasionally occurs; and such a mistake, when it has once been made, has a tend- ency to recur, the clerk having before him, and being to a large extent guided by, the cor- responding account of the preceding year. We have, for example, found Isabel Countess of Mar called Euphemia in 1456 ;1 and in a passage in the present volume J ames Dunbar Earl of Moray is called Thomas? a mistake which at one time led Mr Riddell to suppose that the wives of the second Lord Crichton and of Archibald Douglas were not sisters but cousins.3
